WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.590 --> 00:00:04.080
Prof: Okay,
I need two volunteers here at

00:00:04.080 --> 00:00:06.040
the beginning,
while we're waiting for

00:00:06.040 --> 00:00:07.630
everybody else to come in.
 

00:00:07.630 --> 00:00:11.460
You have to come up here and do
something.

00:00:11.460 --> 00:00:13.230
Come on up.
 

00:00:19.840 --> 00:00:21.550
Okay.
 

00:00:21.550 --> 00:00:24.020
So each of you -- actually I
don't want two people that are

00:00:24.020 --> 00:00:24.830
sitting together.
 

00:00:24.830 --> 00:00:28.800
So Lucas, you;
and Julia stay.

00:00:28.800 --> 00:00:30.970
But Rick, why don't you come up?
 

00:00:30.970 --> 00:00:33.020
So here, come here, come here.
 

00:00:33.020 --> 00:00:36.400
So your job is to grind -- this
is a spice -- so you grind it up

00:00:36.400 --> 00:00:39.619
good, and then we're going to
take it back and show it to the

00:00:39.619 --> 00:00:42.130
people around you;
we're going to smell it.

00:00:42.130 --> 00:00:43.210
Okay?
 

00:00:43.210 --> 00:00:48.060
See if you can -- you have to
really grind it,

00:00:48.060 --> 00:00:50.000
like this, look.
 

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:53.060
Okay?
 

00:00:53.060 --> 00:00:55.980
So we've got two spices here
that we need to identify.

00:01:05.549 --> 00:01:08.355
Okay, you can go back and grind
them at your seat and then show

00:01:08.355 --> 00:01:09.260
it your neighbors.
 

00:01:09.260 --> 00:01:11.299
Later on I'm going to ask you
whether you know what it is.

00:01:17.450 --> 00:01:20.998
Okay, so here's how we're going
through the history of organic

00:01:20.998 --> 00:01:24.200
chemistry and the development of
the molecular model.

00:01:24.200 --> 00:01:25.860
So generation by generation.
 

00:01:25.860 --> 00:01:29.810
And last time we got up to
students of Kekulé,

00:01:29.810 --> 00:01:34.330
who actually did experiments to
allow people to figure out

00:01:34.330 --> 00:01:38.730
something about structure,
not only what was connected to

00:01:38.730 --> 00:01:40.800
what --
that's constitution;

00:01:40.800 --> 00:01:43.560
remember, the nature and the
sequence of bonds.

00:01:43.560 --> 00:01:46.250
So we had composition,
what elements are there,

00:01:46.250 --> 00:01:48.590
what ratio they're in,
how many atoms.

00:01:48.590 --> 00:01:49.660
Right?
 

00:01:49.660 --> 00:01:52.849
Then constitution,
the nature and sequence in

00:01:52.849 --> 00:01:53.430
bonds.
 

00:01:53.430 --> 00:01:56.447
And now we're going to see if
you can go beyond that,

00:01:56.447 --> 00:01:59.000
without cheating and using
X-ray diffraction,

00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:01.959
to figure out how things are
arranged in space;

00:02:01.959 --> 00:02:02.930
so structure.
 

00:02:02.930 --> 00:02:07.113
And we talked last time about
Koerner's proof of positions in

00:02:07.113 --> 00:02:09.675
benzene,
and his proof that all the

00:02:09.675 --> 00:02:13.340
positions in benzene were
equivalent to one another.

00:02:13.340 --> 00:02:15.740
And today we're going to go
really to the next generation.

00:02:15.740 --> 00:02:18.703
Koerner wasn't all that much
younger than -- or he was at

00:02:18.703 --> 00:02:20.818
least halfway in the generation
there.

00:02:20.818 --> 00:02:24.669
But van't Hoff is a full
generation beyond.

00:02:24.669 --> 00:02:25.938
So we're going to look at him.
 

00:02:25.938 --> 00:02:28.514
It says under him
"tetrahedron",

00:02:28.514 --> 00:02:31.970
and it says down here
"tetrahedral carbon".

00:02:31.970 --> 00:02:39.187
And also we'll see something
about Albert Ladenburg and about

00:02:39.187 --> 00:02:42.916
your, whatever,
great-great-chem

00:02:42.916 --> 00:02:48.449
ical-grandfather,
Peter Kohler at Harvard.

00:02:48.449 --> 00:02:51.543
Okay, so as we were closing
last time we were looking at

00:02:51.543 --> 00:02:55.030
this definite picture of the
arrangement of atoms in space,

00:02:55.030 --> 00:02:57.470
where the models are clearly
real models,

00:02:57.470 --> 00:03:01.430
held together by rubber tubing,
and they're tetrahedral,

00:03:01.430 --> 00:03:04.687
and it explains why there can
be three isomers of

00:03:04.687 --> 00:03:09.478
disubstituted --
symmetrically disubstituted --

00:03:09.478 --> 00:03:10.430
ethane.
 

00:03:10.430 --> 00:03:12.270
Of course it was wrong.
 

00:03:12.270 --> 00:03:15.337
Do you know why it was wrong,
why there are not three

00:03:15.337 --> 00:03:16.460
different models?
 

00:03:16.460 --> 00:03:17.568
Yeah.
 

00:03:17.568 --> 00:03:20.788
Because you can rotate about
the middle bond freely;

00:03:20.788 --> 00:03:23.650
it's not frozen in one rotation
here.

00:03:23.650 --> 00:03:24.680
Or is it?
 

00:03:24.680 --> 00:03:26.870
We'll see something about that
later on.

00:03:26.870 --> 00:03:30.370
That turns out to be what's
called conformation.

00:03:30.370 --> 00:03:32.479
Remember, that's one of the C's.
 

00:03:32.479 --> 00:03:36.514
But now we're in configuration,
how things are attached to the

00:03:36.514 --> 00:03:37.440
tetrahedron.
 

00:03:37.440 --> 00:03:40.990
Okay, so after Paternó
had published that,

00:03:40.990 --> 00:03:43.500
he got a letter from his former
sponsor,

00:03:43.500 --> 00:03:46.300
who had moved on,
Adolf Lieben,

00:03:46.300 --> 00:03:50.410
an Austrian who was at this
time in Italy;

00:03:50.410 --> 00:03:56.666
first in Palermo and then,
at this time I think he was in

00:03:56.666 --> 00:04:00.911
Northern Italy,
I think, in Pisa -- oh,

00:04:00.911 --> 00:04:03.360
Torino;
it says up at the top,

00:04:03.360 --> 00:04:04.802
"Torino,
25th of June,

00:04:04.802 --> 00:04:05.580
1869."
 

00:04:05.580 --> 00:04:07.900
And you can see a translation
there if you click.

00:04:07.900 --> 00:04:11.560
But anyhow it says:
"My dear Emmanuele."

00:04:11.560 --> 00:04:13.133
(They corresponded,
like several of these people

00:04:13.133 --> 00:04:16.879
who were great friends;
were for a very long time.)

00:04:16.879 --> 00:04:20.064
"Permit me to make an
observation regarding the

00:04:20.064 --> 00:04:23.500
isomerism pointed out by you and
by Cannizzaro."

00:04:23.500 --> 00:04:25.377
(It's a little bit misleading
to say "by

00:04:25.377 --> 00:04:26.189
Cannizzaro."
 

00:04:26.189 --> 00:04:29.315
He was very cautious about
this, as you know,

00:04:29.315 --> 00:04:31.519
but he introduced the paper.)
 

00:04:31.519 --> 00:04:33.500
"Between"
(and he shows those two

00:04:33.500 --> 00:04:34.350
structures here.
 

00:04:34.350 --> 00:04:37.990
Which look like type
structures, with those brackets.

00:04:37.990 --> 00:04:42.968
And you can see what's fastened
on the two carbons is H^2Cl

00:04:42.968 --> 00:04:45.199
H^2Cl, and H^2Cl,
H^2Cl.

00:04:45.199 --> 00:04:48.218
But he wrote the Cl's
differently, obviously meaning

00:04:48.218 --> 00:04:51.180
to denote this difference in
phase of rotation.)

00:04:51.180 --> 00:04:55.509
"Certainly it's not
absurd, this kind of isomerism,

00:04:55.509 --> 00:04:59.761
even without any differences
among the four valences of

00:04:59.761 --> 00:05:01.100
carbon."
 

00:05:01.100 --> 00:05:04.990
(Remember one could've been
straight, one crooked,

00:05:04.990 --> 00:05:08.009
short, long or something like
that.)

00:05:08.009 --> 00:05:11.697
"I believe, however,
that I don't err when I suppose

00:05:11.697 --> 00:05:15.865
that the same cause which keeps
me from accepting it will also

00:05:15.865 --> 00:05:19.009
keep all the other chemists from
doing so,

00:05:19.009 --> 00:05:22.899
in a silent agreement with one
another.

00:05:22.899 --> 00:05:26.985
You perhaps haven't thought
that accepting this kind of

00:05:26.985 --> 00:05:31.225
isomerism crosses the Rubicon
which separates speculation

00:05:31.225 --> 00:05:35.766
that's considered legitimate
about the mode of combination of

00:05:35.766 --> 00:05:40.004
atoms from speculation which is
less legitimate about the

00:05:40.004 --> 00:05:43.410
position of the atoms in
space."

00:05:43.410 --> 00:05:46.863
(And notice here that he added
as an afterthought,

00:05:46.863 --> 00:05:50.178
vero;
the true position of the atoms

00:05:50.178 --> 00:05:53.593
in space, rather than just
chemical position.

00:05:53.593 --> 00:05:54.370
Right?)
 

00:05:54.370 --> 00:05:57.410
"In all speculations that
have been made up to this time,

00:05:57.410 --> 00:06:02.682
people have always been careful
never to let enter in either the

00:06:02.682 --> 00:06:07.454
relative positions in space
(Distances and surroundings of

00:06:07.454 --> 00:06:08.709
the atoms).
 

00:06:08.709 --> 00:06:12.076
This idea doesn't even enter
into the speculations of

00:06:12.076 --> 00:06:14.406
Kekulé
about isomerism and the

00:06:14.406 --> 00:06:16.088
aromatic series."
 

00:06:16.088 --> 00:06:22.000
(So he draws the picture of the
hexagon and numbers 1 to 6.)

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:24.680
"Kekulé
believes that chlorine 1,

00:06:24.680 --> 00:06:29.072
chlorine 2 positions is
different from chlorine 1,3 and

00:06:29.072 --> 00:06:31.733
from 1,4,
because in the first case the

00:06:31.733 --> 00:06:34.812
two carbon chlorines find
themselves combined with one

00:06:34.812 --> 00:06:37.216
another,
but in the second case they're

00:06:37.216 --> 00:06:39.985
separated by CH,
and in the third case they're

00:06:39.985 --> 00:06:41.370
separated by two CH's.
 

00:06:41.370 --> 00:06:44.838
And to accept this,
one has no need to make

00:06:44.838 --> 00:06:49.379
hypotheses about the
surroundings of the atoms."

00:06:49.379 --> 00:06:51.680
That's really weird isn't it?
 

00:06:51.680 --> 00:06:53.968
He says in one case they're
connected to one another,

00:06:53.968 --> 00:06:56.564
in another case there's a CH in
between, and in another case

00:06:56.564 --> 00:06:58.060
there are two CH's in between.
 

00:06:58.060 --> 00:07:00.740
But to talk about this you
don't have to talk about the

00:07:00.740 --> 00:07:02.129
surroundings of the atoms.
 

00:07:02.129 --> 00:07:05.649
That doesn't make sense to us,
right?

00:07:05.649 --> 00:07:08.105
But it's the difference between
drawing a graph,

00:07:08.105 --> 00:07:10.718
which is just a graph,
and drawing something that's

00:07:10.718 --> 00:07:12.810
supposed to show something in
space.

00:07:12.810 --> 00:07:17.363
He goes on and says,
"It could be that the two

00:07:17.363 --> 00:07:21.242
chlorines in positions 1,
2 are in truth more distant

00:07:21.242 --> 00:07:24.629
from one another than the ones
in positions 1,4!"

00:07:24.629 --> 00:07:29.250
(And he draws an exclamation
point there.

00:07:29.250 --> 00:07:30.290
Right?)
 

00:07:30.290 --> 00:07:33.839
"This just doesn't enter
into Kekulé's hypothesis.

00:07:33.839 --> 00:07:37.497
Making hypotheses about the
relative positions of the atoms

00:07:37.497 --> 00:07:41.470
in space would make possible two
isomers of dichloromethane,

00:07:44.550 --> 00:07:47.055
even accepting the symmetry of
the four valencesâ€¦"

00:07:47.055 --> 00:07:49.214
(That is,
that all the valences of a

00:07:49.214 --> 00:07:51.839
single carbon are equal to one
another.)

00:07:51.839 --> 00:07:55.009
"â€¦and the existence
of a single isomer of methyl

00:07:55.009 --> 00:07:55.600
chloride.
 

00:07:55.600 --> 00:07:57.894
For example,"
And he draws the two structures

00:07:57.894 --> 00:08:00.206
here, the ones where the
chlorines are far from one

00:08:00.206 --> 00:08:02.290
another and when they're near
one another;

00:08:02.290 --> 00:08:06.035
but that's just the graph,
that's not where they are in

00:08:06.035 --> 00:08:06.588
space.
 

00:08:06.588 --> 00:08:07.023
Okay.
 

00:08:07.023 --> 00:08:11.353
He added as an afterthought
between the lines here,

00:08:11.353 --> 00:08:15.596
"There would also result
two isomers of ethyl

00:08:15.596 --> 00:08:17.329
chloride."
 

00:08:17.329 --> 00:08:23.528
"I repeat that I don't
consider this kind of isomerism

00:08:23.528 --> 00:08:24.490
absurd.
 

00:08:24.490 --> 00:08:29.196
But since we have no means to
know the topographic position of

00:08:29.196 --> 00:08:31.709
the atoms,
while we have many to know how

00:08:31.709 --> 00:08:33.519
they are connected to one
another,

00:08:33.519 --> 00:08:38.090
I consider it a bit dangerous
for science.

00:08:38.090 --> 00:08:41.092
Shooting off into space in
search of atoms,

00:08:41.092 --> 00:08:44.740
one risks losing the ground
under his feet."

00:08:44.740 --> 00:08:45.397
(Right?
 

00:08:45.397 --> 00:08:48.308
So be careful former student.)
 

00:08:48.308 --> 00:08:50.426
"Greeting to Cannizzaro,
and Koerner,

00:08:50.426 --> 00:08:50.840
Amato.
 

00:08:50.840 --> 00:08:52.279
I'll write soon to Compisi.
 

00:08:52.279 --> 00:08:55.870
Your friend, Adolf Lieben."
 

00:08:55.870 --> 00:08:57.408
Okay, so be careful.
 

00:08:57.408 --> 00:08:59.980
This isn't what structures are
about, right?

00:08:59.980 --> 00:09:03.070
They're just graphs that show
constitution.

00:09:03.070 --> 00:09:04.674
So here's Koerner,
you remember,

00:09:04.674 --> 00:09:07.418
before he went south,
in Ghent, with Kekulé.

00:09:07.418 --> 00:09:10.899
And on the right of this group
is Albert Ladenburg who,

00:09:10.899 --> 00:09:13.450
once you know,
once you've read what he wrote,

00:09:13.450 --> 00:09:16.658
you can sort of read into his
attitude there,

00:09:16.658 --> 00:09:20.710
that he was a hard guy to deal
with.

00:09:20.710 --> 00:09:21.034
Okay?
 

00:09:21.034 --> 00:09:24.099
He thought he knew a lot,
and he did know a lot,

00:09:24.099 --> 00:09:26.250
but not as much as he thought.
 

00:09:26.250 --> 00:09:29.778
So he published this paper the
next year, in 1869;

00:09:29.778 --> 00:09:32.340
or the same year that
Paternó

00:09:32.340 --> 00:09:33.950
published his thing.
 

00:09:33.950 --> 00:09:36.942
"Kekulé
adopts two hypotheses:

00:09:36.942 --> 00:09:41.250
(1) The 6 hydrogen atoms of
benzene are equivalent;"

00:09:41.250 --> 00:09:45.475
(that's what Koerner actually
proved) "and (2) Each

00:09:45.475 --> 00:09:50.085
hydrogen atom of benzene has two
sets of two others which are

00:09:50.085 --> 00:09:53.620
symmetrically arranged with
respect to it;

00:09:53.620 --> 00:09:59.942
that is, 1.2 is the same as
1.6, and 1.3 is the same as 1.5,

00:09:59.942 --> 00:10:04.980
although 4 is unique with
respect to 1."

00:10:04.980 --> 00:10:05.364
(Okay?
 

00:10:05.364 --> 00:10:08.629
So there are two that are
symmetrically arranged.)

00:10:08.629 --> 00:10:12.480
"Already several years ago
I had occasion to make

00:10:12.480 --> 00:10:15.169
Kekulé
aware that his graphical

00:10:15.169 --> 00:10:18.149
formula for benzene is not
adequate,

00:10:18.149 --> 00:10:21.720
since here 1.2 and 1.6 must be
inequivalent,

00:10:21.720 --> 00:10:25.991
while one could have various
views about whether positions 3

00:10:25.991 --> 00:10:28.600
and 5 are equivalent or
not."

00:10:28.600 --> 00:10:31.551
Why would one and two be
certainly -- two and six,

00:10:31.551 --> 00:10:33.599
that is, be certainly
inequivalent,

00:10:33.599 --> 00:10:36.129
but three and five might or
might not?

00:10:40.379 --> 00:10:41.779
Yeah, Kate?
 

00:10:41.779 --> 00:10:45.981
Student:  Because
between one and two is a double

00:10:45.981 --> 00:10:49.649
bond and between one and six is
a single bond.

00:10:49.649 --> 00:10:51.669
Prof: Both have a single
and a double.

00:10:51.669 --> 00:10:55.850
But what about 1.3 and 1.5?
 

00:10:55.850 --> 00:10:58.168
Are they 100% equivalent?
 

00:10:58.168 --> 00:11:00.918
Student: 
&gt;.

00:11:00.918 --> 00:11:01.615
Prof: Ah ha!
 

00:11:01.615 --> 00:11:03.777
because one is single-double
and the other is double-single,

00:11:03.777 --> 00:11:04.620
going the other way.
 

00:11:04.620 --> 00:11:08.440
So that might or might not be
equivalent, Ladenburg says.

00:11:08.440 --> 00:11:11.519
"Both conditions could,
however, be fulfilled through

00:11:11.519 --> 00:11:14.385
alternative formulas which,
so far as I know,

00:11:14.385 --> 00:11:16.600
have not been proposed
before."

00:11:16.600 --> 00:11:19.960
So here are Ladenburg's
formulas.

00:11:19.960 --> 00:11:23.548
And the one in the middle,
the triangular prism,

00:11:23.548 --> 00:11:26.048
actually came to be called,
100 years later,

00:11:26.048 --> 00:11:28.972
or a little,
seventy years later,

00:11:28.972 --> 00:11:31.440
Ladenburg benzene,
right?

00:11:31.440 --> 00:11:33.279
Because someone was able to
synthesize that.

00:11:33.279 --> 00:11:37.480
It's also called prismane,
because it looks like a prism,

00:11:37.480 --> 00:11:38.080
right?
 

00:11:38.080 --> 00:11:41.788
And then there's this funny
structure on the right.

00:11:41.788 --> 00:11:48.240
Okay, so this is 1872,
and we're going to --

00:11:48.240 --> 00:11:52.467
there's van't Hoff,
who is an eighteen-year-old

00:11:52.467 --> 00:11:55.779
student,
come to Bonn to see the great

00:11:55.779 --> 00:11:56.970
Kekulé.
 

00:11:56.970 --> 00:12:02.086
And he writes,
in 1876, at the age of 24,

00:12:02.086 --> 00:12:05.028
a reply to Ladenburg.
 

00:12:05.028 --> 00:12:07.581
"Proof that the prism
formula"

00:12:07.581 --> 00:12:11.248
(of Ladenburg) "suffers
from the same problem as the

00:12:11.248 --> 00:12:15.306
hexagon with fixed double bonds
removes the previously asserted

00:12:15.306 --> 00:12:18.514
superiority from the
former" (from the prism)

00:12:18.514 --> 00:12:21.197
"and makes the original
Kekulé

00:12:21.197 --> 00:12:25.565
notation not only simpler,
but also the presentation with

00:12:25.565 --> 00:12:27.899
which the facts conform
best."

00:12:27.899 --> 00:12:31.264
Because Kekulé
had the idea that what these

00:12:31.264 --> 00:12:35.038
lines really meant was how often
the bonds collide --

00:12:35.038 --> 00:12:37.620
how often the atoms collide
with one another.

00:12:37.620 --> 00:12:39.990
They collide more often,
he thought, when it's a double

00:12:39.990 --> 00:12:41.570
bond than when it's a single
bond.

00:12:41.570 --> 00:12:43.744
So he thought that in this
case, although you would draw

00:12:43.744 --> 00:12:44.841
single,
double, single,

00:12:44.841 --> 00:12:47.551
double, that the number of
collisions actually was the same

00:12:47.551 --> 00:12:48.720
one way and the other.
 

00:12:48.720 --> 00:12:52.852
So you'd draw both formulas to
be in between what we would call

00:12:52.852 --> 00:12:54.519
now resonance formulas.
 

00:12:54.519 --> 00:12:57.899
So anyhow, this young student,
twenty-four years old now,

00:12:57.899 --> 00:13:01.139
says Ladenburg's off base in
saying the prism is better,

00:13:01.139 --> 00:13:05.586
because it has the same problem
and you can't get out of it with

00:13:05.586 --> 00:13:07.210
this vibration thing.
 

00:13:07.210 --> 00:13:11.865
Okay, "The 1,2; 5,6;
and 3,4 derivatives are

00:13:11.865 --> 00:13:15.519
completely similar,
although differing from 4,5;

00:13:15.519 --> 00:13:17.139
2,3; 6,1."
 

00:13:17.139 --> 00:13:22.039
So 1,2; 5,6;
and 3,4 are completely similar.

