00:40:35.369 --> 00:40:35.702
Okay?
 

00:40:35.702 --> 00:40:39.835
Sometimes too many isomers are
predicted, like Paternó's

00:40:39.835 --> 00:40:40.969
dibromoethane.
 

00:40:40.969 --> 00:40:42.719
He had different phases of
rotation;

00:40:42.719 --> 00:40:44.079
said those were different.
 

00:40:44.079 --> 00:40:45.711
In fact, they weren't
different, it was just

00:40:45.711 --> 00:40:48.179
experimental errors of someone
who thought they were different.

00:40:48.179 --> 00:40:52.250
So sometimes the model predicts
too many isomers.

00:40:52.250 --> 00:40:56.440
But often, or sometimes at
least, it predicts too few;

00:40:56.440 --> 00:40:59.900
as in the case of maleic and
fumaric acid where you have a

00:40:59.900 --> 00:41:00.750
double bond.
 

00:41:00.750 --> 00:41:03.960
There are two different
substances with different

00:41:03.960 --> 00:41:06.099
melting points and properties.
 

00:41:06.099 --> 00:41:10.561
With lactic acid -- remember
that Scheele had found lactic

00:41:10.561 --> 00:41:15.018
acid from milk,
but Liebig had found it from

00:41:15.018 --> 00:41:17.673
meat --
and they were the same,

00:41:17.673 --> 00:41:22.329
it was found out about this
time by a guy named Wislicenus.

00:41:22.329 --> 00:41:25.856
They had the same constitution,
but one rotated to the right

00:41:25.856 --> 00:41:28.010
and the other rotated to the
left.

00:41:28.010 --> 00:41:30.320
There was tartaric and racemic
acid;

00:41:30.320 --> 00:41:33.893
which was even more complicated
because there was also

00:41:33.893 --> 00:41:38.072
meso-tartaric and also what came
to be called l-tartaric

00:41:38.072 --> 00:41:38.679
acid.
 

00:41:38.679 --> 00:41:41.349
And that was the discovery of
Pasteur.

00:41:41.349 --> 00:41:45.940
So in 1848, which was another
revolutionary time in France,

00:41:45.940 --> 00:41:49.498
Pasteur was twenty-six years
old and was becoming an

00:41:49.498 --> 00:41:52.429
interdisciplinary scientist:
chemistry,

00:41:52.429 --> 00:41:55.460
physics, crystallography,
all he was studying.

00:41:55.460 --> 00:41:59.451
And he wrote a paper called
"On the relations that can

00:41:59.451 --> 00:42:03.235
exist among crystalline
form," (so crystallography)

00:42:03.235 --> 00:42:05.436
"chemical
composition,"

00:42:05.436 --> 00:42:08.672
(chemistry) "
and the direction of rotatory

00:42:08.672 --> 00:42:10.530
polarization."
 

00:42:10.530 --> 00:42:15.476
That is this stuff we're
talking about,

00:42:15.476 --> 00:42:17.949
which is physics.
 

00:42:17.949 --> 00:42:21.527
Now remember we talked about
Mitscherlich and the ability to

00:42:21.527 --> 00:42:25.228
measure angles on crystals and
tell -- distinguish crystals by

00:42:25.228 --> 00:42:26.260
their angles.
 

00:42:26.260 --> 00:42:32.619
So these are pictures that
Pasteur was using to draw his

00:42:32.619 --> 00:42:35.510
salts of tartaric acid.
 

00:42:35.510 --> 00:42:39.063
In particular sodium -- it's a
diacid, and so you can have

00:42:39.063 --> 00:42:42.170
different cations;
sodium ammonium tartrate is

00:42:42.170 --> 00:42:42.860
this one.
 

00:42:42.860 --> 00:42:47.280
And there's his picture that he
drew of it.

00:42:47.280 --> 00:42:51.376
And he said -- mostly you see
the faces that are shown in that

00:42:51.376 --> 00:42:55.139
picture, but sometimes you can
see other little faces.

00:42:55.139 --> 00:42:56.320
Right?
 

00:42:56.320 --> 00:42:59.849
And you notice that the
crystals have symmetry.

00:42:59.849 --> 00:43:03.606
They have a horizontal plane of
symmetry and also a vertical

00:43:03.606 --> 00:43:04.880
plane of symmetry.
 

00:43:04.880 --> 00:43:06.300
Right?
 

00:43:06.300 --> 00:43:09.159
So if you can see one of those
edges,

00:43:09.159 --> 00:43:12.313
you should see the others that
are related by symmetry this

00:43:12.313 --> 00:43:14.016
direction,
symmetry this direction,

00:43:14.016 --> 00:43:15.429
and also symmetry this
direction.

00:43:15.429 --> 00:43:20.139
So you should see all eight,
in the tartrate.

00:43:20.139 --> 00:43:23.228
But always only four of them
are observed,

00:43:23.228 --> 00:43:27.050
in sodium ammonium tartrate;
not all eight.

00:43:27.050 --> 00:43:29.938
Mitscherlich had studied this
stuff, and he was sort of the

00:43:29.938 --> 00:43:31.880
father of measuring angles like
this.

00:43:31.880 --> 00:43:34.652
But when Pasteur was trying to
learn the technique and repeat

00:43:34.652 --> 00:43:36.380
it,
he noticed that you don't very

00:43:36.380 --> 00:43:38.170
often get these edges all
together,

00:43:38.170 --> 00:43:39.489
these little tiny ones.
 

00:43:39.489 --> 00:43:41.630
It usually looks like the
original picture did.

00:43:41.630 --> 00:43:45.567
But when those sharp edges are
truncated by little additional

00:43:45.567 --> 00:43:48.980
faces, you only see four,
you don't see all eight.

00:43:48.980 --> 00:43:52.719
So Mitscherlich had reported
that the -- now howâ€¦?

00:43:52.719 --> 00:43:55.219
-- That was tartrate, right?
 

00:43:55.219 --> 00:43:57.719
Now they had the idea that
racemate,

00:43:57.719 --> 00:43:59.768
which remember didn't rotate
light --

00:43:59.768 --> 00:44:03.396
Pasteur's idea was that
molecules were twisted in a

00:44:03.396 --> 00:44:06.079
right-hand or a left-handed
helix,

00:44:06.079 --> 00:44:08.460
and therefore they had this
effect on light,

00:44:08.460 --> 00:44:09.789
to make it twist.
 

00:44:09.789 --> 00:44:10.739
Right?
 

00:44:10.739 --> 00:44:15.000
But one's that aren't twisted,
like racemic acid --

00:44:15.000 --> 00:44:16.880
Where the molecules aren't
twisted,

00:44:16.880 --> 00:44:20.130
then, at least in those,
you should see all eight,

00:44:20.130 --> 00:44:23.039
because you will have mirror
images.

00:44:23.039 --> 00:44:24.030
Okay?
 

00:44:24.030 --> 00:44:26.601
So he thought untwisted
molecules would be what's called

00:44:26.601 --> 00:44:29.780
"holohedral";
that is, have all their faces.

00:44:29.780 --> 00:44:34.347
So he studied the sodium
ammonium racemate and was quite

00:44:34.347 --> 00:44:39.000
surprised to find that sometimes
he saw the red ones,

00:44:39.000 --> 00:44:42.809
sometimes he saw the green
ones, but never on the same

00:44:42.809 --> 00:44:43.530
crystal.
 

00:44:43.530 --> 00:44:47.467
Some crystals were right,
red, and some were left,

00:44:47.467 --> 00:44:48.110
green.
 

00:44:48.110 --> 00:44:51.800
So he separated those crystals,
the right ones from the left

00:44:51.800 --> 00:44:52.239
ones.
 

00:44:52.239 --> 00:44:54.931
He wrote: "I carefully
separated the right from the

00:44:54.931 --> 00:44:57.869
left crystals and observing
their dissolution separately,

00:44:57.869 --> 00:45:00.795
with Monsieur Biot's
polarization apparatus"

00:45:00.795 --> 00:45:04.086
(the thing that measures the
rotation) "I saw with

00:45:04.086 --> 00:45:07.501
surprise and delight that the
right crystals deviated the

00:45:07.501 --> 00:45:10.731
plane of polarization to the
right and the left to the

00:45:10.731 --> 00:45:11.889
left."
 

00:45:11.889 --> 00:45:15.869
So why did racemic acid not
rotate light?

00:45:15.869 --> 00:45:19.268
Student:
&gt;

00:45:19.268 --> 00:45:21.617
Prof: Because it was a
50:50 mixture of things that

00:45:21.617 --> 00:45:24.146
would rotate it one way --
it's not that it was untwisted

00:45:24.146 --> 00:45:26.853
-- it was that some of them
would rotate it one way and some

00:45:26.853 --> 00:45:29.079
would rotate it the other,
and they'd cancel out.

00:45:32.510 --> 00:45:32.987
Okay.
 

00:45:32.987 --> 00:45:37.967
Oops I improved this and forgot
to take that one out;

00:45:37.967 --> 00:45:38.829
sorry.
 

00:45:38.829 --> 00:45:41.389
Okay, so now he knows what's
going on,

00:45:41.389 --> 00:45:45.739
that racemic acid is actually a
50:50 mixture of right-handed,

00:45:45.739 --> 00:45:49.530
dextro-tartaric acid,
d, that has a plus

00:45:49.530 --> 00:45:53.072
rotation,
and left-handed tartaric acid,

00:45:53.072 --> 00:45:55.438
l,
levo, which has a minus

00:45:55.438 --> 00:45:57.860
rotation, but the same melting
point,

00:45:57.860 --> 00:46:01.949
the same rotation,
but opposite in direction.

00:46:01.949 --> 00:46:04.570
So those are mirror images of
one another.

00:46:04.570 --> 00:46:07.320
And the racemic acid is a 50:50
mixture.

00:46:07.320 --> 00:46:09.510
Now this was 1848.
 

00:46:09.510 --> 00:46:12.360
So that's a long time from
where we've gotten to.

00:46:12.360 --> 00:46:12.773
Right?
 

00:46:12.773 --> 00:46:15.880
That was ten years before the
idea of bonds.

00:46:15.880 --> 00:46:19.469
Okay?
 

00:46:19.469 --> 00:46:21.601
So that was
"resolution",

00:46:21.601 --> 00:46:24.989
the separation of a mixture
into the two components.

00:46:24.989 --> 00:46:25.476
Right?
 

00:46:25.476 --> 00:46:28.070
But what is meso-tartaric acid?
 

00:46:28.070 --> 00:46:30.059
Why doesn't it rotate?
 

00:46:30.059 --> 00:46:33.186
So now we go forward,
twenty-four years,

00:46:33.186 --> 00:46:37.914
to Bonn, and there's van't Hoff
studying with Kekulé,

00:46:37.914 --> 00:46:39.920
at the age of twenty.
 

00:46:39.920 --> 00:46:42.949
So that's a quarter of a
century.

00:46:42.949 --> 00:46:44.389
That's a long time, right?
 

00:46:44.389 --> 00:46:46.440
It's longer than you've lived.
 

00:46:46.440 --> 00:46:47.769
So here's van't Hoff.
 

00:46:47.769 --> 00:46:51.110
He had some opinion of himself.
 

00:46:51.110 --> 00:46:56.617
He won the first Nobel Prize --
I mean, he had a high opinion

00:46:56.617 --> 00:47:02.309
that was completely justified --
in 1901, the first Nobel Prize

00:47:02.309 --> 00:47:03.869
in Chemistry.
 

00:47:03.869 --> 00:47:06.262
And he didn't get it for this,
which he should've gotten it

00:47:06.262 --> 00:47:06.510
for.
 

00:47:06.510 --> 00:47:09.280
He got for inventing physical
chemistry.

00:47:09.280 --> 00:47:16.360
The most admired trait he had
was imagination.

00:47:16.360 --> 00:47:18.139
So he liked poets and artists.
 

00:47:18.139 --> 00:47:22.460
In fact, his hero was Lord
Byron.

00:47:22.460 --> 00:47:26.329
Look at that.
 

00:47:26.329 --> 00:47:28.630
Okay?
 

00:47:28.630 --> 00:47:32.659
And in 1874,
as we said, he was a student.

00:47:32.659 --> 00:47:36.460
And he wrote this,
a pamphlet, in Dutch,

00:47:36.460 --> 00:47:40.103
which was then translated into
German and called "The

00:47:40.103 --> 00:47:43.492
Arrangement of Atoms in
Space," and was published

00:47:43.492 --> 00:47:44.260
in 1877.
 

00:47:44.260 --> 00:47:47.820
It was fifty-three pages long
and heavily illustrated.

00:47:47.820 --> 00:47:50.340
And look at the website for
this.

00:47:50.340 --> 00:47:53.940
One of the Wikis I've assigned
is that website.

00:47:53.940 --> 00:47:59.208
And also this website about
criticism of van't Hoff by a guy

00:47:59.208 --> 00:48:00.460
named Kolbe.
 

00:48:00.460 --> 00:48:01.730
So here's Hermann Kolbe.
 

00:48:01.730 --> 00:48:04.956
He was twice,
more than twice van't Hoff's

00:48:04.956 --> 00:48:08.500
age, and a pillar of traditional
chemistry.

00:48:08.500 --> 00:48:12.030
He wrote, in a review of this
book: "It is completely

00:48:12.030 --> 00:48:15.561
impossible to criticize this
booklet in any detail because

00:48:15.561 --> 00:48:19.030
the fancy trifles in it are
totally devoid of any factual

00:48:19.030 --> 00:48:22.067
reality and are completely
incomprehensible to any

00:48:22.067 --> 00:48:24.050
clear-minded researcher.
 

00:48:24.050 --> 00:48:27.996
The brochure begins with the
words: 'The modern chemical

00:48:27.996 --> 00:48:29.969
theory has two weak points.
 

00:48:29.969 --> 00:48:33.228
It says nothing either about
the relative position or the

00:48:33.228 --> 00:48:36.195
motion of the atoms within the
molecules.'"

00:48:36.195 --> 00:48:37.710
This is absurd,
right?

00:48:37.710 --> 00:48:40.659
But he was wrong.
 

00:48:40.659 --> 00:48:41.679
Right?
 

00:48:41.679 --> 00:48:44.059
Now am I like Kekulé?
 

00:48:44.059 --> 00:48:46.550
Because I'm more than twice as
old as you are.

00:48:46.550 --> 00:48:46.940
Right?
 

00:48:46.940 --> 00:48:50.599
So those are three websites you
should read about this.

00:48:50.599 --> 00:48:53.416
But, in fact,
it's not true that van't Hoff

00:48:53.416 --> 00:48:55.900
was devoid of any factual
reality,

00:48:55.900 --> 00:48:57.900
because we've already seen some
of his evidence,

00:48:57.900 --> 00:49:00.420
and we'll see more next time.
 

